Why can ISIS persist?
The deadly terrorist attacks in New York, Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad demonstrate that the Islamic State (ISIS) has spread its influence to multiple regions in Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS remains powerful in Syria and Iraq, the longer its terrorist network will continue to orchestrate such massacres.
However, ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem lies in the fact that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not considered ISIS as their primary enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small-scale fighting force, with the US estimating around 20,000 to 25,000 members in Iraq and Syria, and approximately 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the active military forces of Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is insignificant.
In September 2014, US President Obama pledged to "strike and ultimately destroy" ISIS, but the US and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), have consistently focused on toppling Syria's Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, Israeli Major General Herzi Halevy bluntly stated (as reported to me by a journalist who was present at Halevy's speech): "Israel does not want to see the Syrian situation end with (ISIS) defeated, superpowers leaving the region, and (Israel) facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but Israel's greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two major quasi-military opponents — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad rather than defeating ISIS.
Under neoconservative influence, the Syrian war was seen by the United States as a continuation of the global U.S. hegemony plan proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told U.S. General Wesley Clark:
"But we (from the Gulf War) did learn one thing, that we can use force in the region - in the Middle East - and the Soviets will not stop us."
"We have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regime - Syria, Iran (as mentioned), Iraq, etc. - before the next superpower challenges us."
American wars in the Middle East - Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. - are to make the Soviets and subsequent Russians exit the competition, and establish American hegemony.
These "efforts" have been disastrous.
For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the main goal is to topple Assad to weaken Iran.
Syria is part of a massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, with the conflict unfolding in Syria and Yemen, as well as in Bahrain and other countries in the region with sectarian tendencies (including Saudi Arabia itself) where the Shia-Sunni confrontation is more intense.
Toppling Assad would strengthen Turkey's regional position.
However, Turkey now faces three opponents on its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and the nationalist Kurds.
So far, ISIS is less important to Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
However, ISIS's terrorist attacks in Turkey could change this dynamic.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and supporting non-military actions.
However, both countries have expressed willingness to cooperate with the US in fighting ISIS and can also cooperate on other issues.
So far, the US has been inactive because its focus is on toppling Assad.
The US foreign policy community has criticized Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia has accused the US of trying to overthrow Assad.
These complaints may seem reciprocal, but they are not.
The US and its allies' attempt to topple Assad violates the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad aligns with Syria's right to self-defense under the charter.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to remove.
The persistence of ISIS exposes three major strategic flaws and a fatal tactical flaw in US foreign policy.
Firstly, neoconservatism's demand for US hegemony through regime change is not only a brutal and ignorant notion; it is also a classic case of imperial overreach.
Every time the US has attempted this, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
The CIA has long armed and trained Sunni jihadists through secret actions funded by Saudi Arabia.
These jihadists in turn gave birth to ISIS, which is a direct (perhaps unintended) consequence of the policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi partners.
Thirdly, the US views Iran and Russia as irreconcilable enemies to a large extent, which is a self-fulfilling prophecy.
It is possible to restructure relations with both countries.
The US has failed in its tactical efforts to win the two-front war against Assad and ISIS.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the al-Nusra Front, fill the vacuum.
If the US, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies can defeat ISIS.
Indeed, Assad will remain in power; indeed, Russia will remain an ally in Syria; indeed, Iran will gain influence in the region.
Terror attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for a period of time still under the ISIS banner; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome would not only eradicate ISIS in the Middle East, but also lay a foundation for a more comprehensive easing of regional tensions.
The US and Russia can start to reverse the recent new Cold War by jointly expelling jihadist terrorism.
(A NATO commitment not to admit Ukraine or upgrade Eastern European missile defense capabilities would also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits as well.
Pursuing a cooperative policy to strike ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to find new temporary arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by allowing Iran to build a cooperative economic and geopolitical relationship with the West, which in turn increases the chances of a gradual Israeli-Palestinian reconciliation.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the current Western —— especially American —— strategic flaws.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The problem is whether the US will undertake the strategic reassessment needed to achieve this goal.
